Objective:
Design a clean and scalable architecture in a Next.js application with a separation of concerns between:

Database Layer

Business Layer (Services + Controllers)

Presentation Layer (API routes, Pages/Components)

📐 Architecture Description:
1. Database Layer
Responsible for all interactions with the database.

Contains ORM/Query logic (e.g., Prisma, Drizzle, TypeORM, or raw queries).

Exposes well-defined functions like getUserById, createOrder, etc.

📁 Structure: lib/db/ or data/
✅ Example: lib/db/userRepository.ts

2. Business Layer
a. Services
Core location of business logic.

Services coordinate multiple database calls and implement business rules.

No request or response objects here.

📁 Structure: services/
✅ Example: services/userService.ts

ts
Copy
Edit
export async function createUser(data: UserInput) {
  // validate input
  // check for existing user
  // call db layer
}
b. Controllers
Thin layer that processes incoming requests (from API routes).

Calls appropriate services.

Maps inputs (e.g., request body) and handles errors or responses.

📁 Structure: controllers/
✅ Example: controllers/userController.ts

ts
Copy
Edit
export async function handleCreateUser(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  try {
    const user = await userService.createUser(req.body);
    res.status(201).json(user);
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(400).json({ message: err.message });
  }
}
3. Presentation Layer
a. API Routes
Located in pages/api/

Delegates logic to controllers only

No business logic here

📁 Example: pages/api/users/index.ts

ts
Copy
Edit
export default async function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === "POST") {
    return handleCreateUser(req, res);
  }
}
b. Pages/Components
Frontend UI using React components and hooks


Calls API routes using fetch, Axios, or React Query